us.ihmc.euclid.referenceFrame

Class FrameVector2D

  • java.lang.Object
    • us.ihmc.euclid.referenceFrame.FrameVector2D
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.Clearable, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.EpsilonComparable<FrameVector2D>, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.GeometricallyComparable<FrameVector2D>, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.GeometryObject<FrameVector2D>, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.Settable<FrameVector2D>, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.Transformable, FixedFrameTuple2DBasics, FixedFrameVector2DBasics, FrameChangeable, FrameTuple2DBasics, FrameTuple2DReadOnly, FrameVector2DBasics, FrameVector2DReadOnly, ReferenceFrameHolder, us.ihmc.euclid.tuple2D.interfaces.Tuple2DBasics, us.ihmc.euclid.tuple2D.interfaces.Tuple2DReadOnly, us.ihmc.euclid.tuple2D.interfaces.Vector2DBasics, us.ihmc.euclid.tuple2D.interfaces.Vector2DReadOnly

    public class FrameVector2D
extends java.lang.Object
implements FrameVector2DBasics, us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.GeometryObject<FrameVector2D>
    FrameVector2D is a 2D vector expressed in a given reference frame.

    In addition to representing a Vector2DBasics, a ReferenceFrame is associated to a FrameVector2D. This allows, for instance, to enforce, at runtime, that operations on vectors occur in the same coordinate system. Also, via the method changeFrame(ReferenceFrame), one can easily calculates the value of a vector in different reference frames.

    Because a FrameVector2D extends Vector2DBasics, it is compatible with methods only requiring Vector2DBasics. However, these methods do NOT assert that the operation occur in the proper coordinate system. Use this feature carefully and always prefer using methods requiring FrameVector2D.

      • changeFrame

        public void changeFrame(ReferenceFrame desiredFrame)
        Transforms this geometry such that the transformation represents the same geometry but from the perspective of another reference frame: desiredFrame.

        Once the geometry is transformed, the reference frame is updated to desiredFrame. In the case, this.referenceFrame == desiredFrame, this method does nothing.

        Specified by:
        changeFrame in interface FrameChangeable
        Parameters:
        desiredFrame - the reference frame in which this geometry is to be expressed.

      • changeFrameAndProjectToXYPlane

        public final void changeFrameAndProjectToXYPlane(ReferenceFrame desiredFrame)
        Performs a transformation of the vector such that it is expressed in a new frame desireFrame.

        Because the transformation between two reference frames is a 3D transformation, the result of transforming this vector 2D can result in a vector 3D. This method projects the result of the transformation onto the XY-plane.

        Specified by:
        changeFrameAndProjectToXYPlane in interface FrameVector2DBasics
        Parameters:
        desiredFrame - the reference frame in which the vector is to be expressed.

      • geometricallyEquals

        public boolean geometricallyEquals(FrameVector2D other,
                                   double epsilon)
        Tests if this and other represent the same vector 2D to an epsilon.

        Two vectors are considered geometrically equal if they are at a distance of less than or equal to epsilon.

        Note that this.geometricallyEquals(other, epsilon) == true does not necessarily imply this.epsilonEquals(other, epsilon) and vice versa.

        Specified by:
        geometricallyEquals in interface us.ihmc.euclid.interfaces.GeometricallyComparable<FrameVector2D>
        Parameters:
        other - the other vector 2D to compare against this. Not modified.
        epsilon - the maximum distance that the two vectors can be spaced and still considered equal.
        Returns:
        true if the two vectors represent the same geometry, false otherwise.
        Throws:
        ReferenceFrameMismatchException - if other is not expressed in the same reference frame as this.
